    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output="Based on the provided financial statement chunks, here are the accounting policies regarding satellite capitalization, general property and equipment, and orbital/flight assets:\n\n### 1. Satellite Capitalization and Accounting\n*   **Costs Capitalized:** Satellite assets include the direct costs to build them (parts, labor, and allocated overhead) as well as capitalized launch costs incurred to get them into orbit. \n*   **Inter-Segment Launches:** When the Space segment launches internal Starlink satellites, no inter-segment revenue is recognized. Instead, the launch costs (which include an allocation of flight vehicle costs) are directly capitalized into the satellite asset within Property, Plant, and Equipment (PP&E).\n*   **Useful Life & Depreciation:** Satellites are depreciated using the **straight-line method**. Useful lives are estimated based on engineering studies, historical on-orbit performance, propellant life, utilization patterns, and planned technology transitions. \n    *   **Broadband satellites:** 5-year useful life.\n    *   **First-generation mobile satellites:** 3-year useful life.\n    *   **General Range:** 3 to 5 years.\n*   **Sensitivity:** A one-year change in the average useful life of satellite assets would impact operating income by approximately $480 million (for the year ended Dec 31, 2025) and $170 million (for the three months ended Mar 31, 2026).\n\n### 2. Property, Plant, and Equipment (General PP&E)\n*   **Capitalization vs. Expensing:** Routine maintenance and repairs are expensed as incurred. Significant refurbishments, renewals, and enhancements that increase an asset's functionality, output, or expected life are capitalized and depreciated ratably over the identified useful life.\n*   **Interest Capitalization:** The company capitalizes interest costs for significant long-term construction projects (such as AI infrastructure data centers and launch facilities). Capitalization begins when preparation activities commence, is calculated using average accumulated expenditures and the company's weighted average borrowing rate, and ceases when the asset is substantially completed. Capitalized interest becomes part of the asset's historical cost.\n*   **Standard Useful Lives:** Depreciated primarily on a straight-line basis over the following estimated lives:\n    *   **Servers and networking equipment:** 5 - 6 years\n    *   **Machinery and equipment:** 3 - 10 years\n    *   **Data center infrastructure:** 20 - 25 years\n    *   **Launch sites:** 7 - 20 years\n    *   **Buildings and improvements:** 30 years\n    *   **Leasehold improvements:** Shorter of 7 - 20 years or the life of the lease\n*   **Impairment & Disposals:** PP&E is evaluated for impairment at the lowest level of independent cash flows whenever events indicate the carrying value may not be recoverable. Routine disposals, scrapping, and gateway decommissions are charged to *Cost of Revenue* or *SG&A*. Abnormal impairments (e.g., damaged hardware, abandoned production lines, facility consolidations) are charged to *Impairment* or *Restructuring* expenses.\n\n### 3. Orbital Assets and Flight Vehicles (Aerospace Hardware)\n*   **Classification (Reusable vs. Expendable vs. Development):**\n    *   **Reusable Hardware:** Boosters (first stages), fairings, Merlin engines, and Dragon capsules are classified as **PP&E**.\n    *   **Non-Reusable (Expendable):** Second stages are not reusable; they are recorded as **Inventory** and expensed to *Cost of Revenue* upon launch or assignment.\n    *   **Development Stage:** Starship (boosters, ships, and Raptor engines) is currently in development. The majority of these costs are expensed to *Research and Development* as incurred, and Raptor engines are expensed when used in test flights.\n*   **Depreciation Method (Flight Cycles):** Unlike standard PP&E, reusable flight vehicles and spacecraft are depreciated based on the **expected number of average flights** (ranging from 5 to 25 flights) rather than a time-based straight-line method.\n*   **Estimating Flight Lives:** Management periodically reviews and estimates the number of flights a vehicle can complete based on:\n    1.  Recovery and refurbishment success rates and economic feasibility (supported by declining refurbishment costs).\n    2.  Customer acceptance limits for reflown hardware.\n    3.  Expected future launches in the mission manifest and anticipated retirement timing (e.g., transitioning from Falcon to Starship).\n*   **Sensitivity:** A change of five more or fewer average remaining flights for flight vehicles and spacecraft would *not* have a material impact on the company's operating income.",
