n space-grade solar technology for unlimited, low-cost power and "radiative cooling architectures" (facing radiator panels toward cold deep space) to manage thermal loads without the operating costs of terrestrial liquid or air cooling.\n\n**3. Starship and Launch Cadence**\n*   **Starship\'s Role:** The deployment strategy is entirely dependent on the heavy-lift capabilities of **Starship**. The filing calculates the 100-gigawatt goal based on Starship V3 delivering **100 metric tons** to orbit per flight (with future V4 generations potentially reaching 200 metric tons).\n*   **Scale and Cadence:** To achieve the 100 GW goal at 100 kW per ton, the company acknowledges it would require transporting approximately one million metric tons to orbit annually, necessitating a massive scale-up to **thousands of Starship launches per year**. \n\n**4. Operational Synergies (Starlink)**\n*   The filing also highlights that the company will leverage its existing Starlink constellation (approx. 9,600 satellites) for automated collision avoidance, orbital debris management, and a dynamic mesh network of inter-satellite lasers to route data globally with low latency. \n\nIn summary, the provided text serves as a comprehensive business overview of the company\'s pivot toward space-based AI data centers, detailing the exact hardware (V3, Starship), physics (solar power, radiative cooling), and economic rationale (bypassing terrestrial power grid limits) required to make orbital AI compute a reality.',
