t permanent damage or reduced performance across the fleet.\n\n### 3. Planned Orbital Infrastructure\nThe company is projecting into entirely unproven markets with novel infrastructure concepts:\n*   **Orbital AI Compute Infrastructure:** The company acknowledges that neither it nor anyone else has previously operated AI compute infrastructure in space. Because the harsh space environment (thermal cycles, radiation, micrometeoroids) cannot be fully replicated in testing, and because orbital hardware cannot be easily repaired or upgraded, component failures could result in permanent capacity loss and accelerated depreciation. Furthermore, the physical lifespan of the satellites is inherently shorter than the IT systems they host, requiring constant replacement launches.\n*   **Lunar and Interplanetary Infrastructure:** The prospectus includes forward-looking statements regarding the size and growth of emerging markets for "lunar-related activities and interplanetary activities," noting that these ventures have lengthy time horizons and involve unprecedented risks.\n\n### 4. Key Risk Factors & Strategic Dependencies\nThe deployment of these future satellites and constellations is tied to several critical risk factors:\n*   **Total Dependency on Starship:** The company explicitly states that its current operational rockets (Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy) are *not* capable of deploying V3 or V2 Mobile satellites. Therefore, the entire growth strategy for next-generation constellations and orbital AI infrastructure is strictly dependent on the successful development, testing, and scaled launch cadence of the **Starship** vehicle. Any delays in Starship will materially delay or limit these deployments.\n*   **Regulatory and Spectrum Hurdles:** Deploying constellations of up to one million satellites will require an unprecedented array of domestic and international approvals, including spectrum authorizations, orbital debris mitigation plans, and space situational awareness co