    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided financial statements and accounting policies, here is the breakdown of SpaceX’s **Starship capitalization trigger, commercialization policy**, and how the **development vs. commercial stage accounting** works for aerospace inventory and reusable flight vehicles.\n\n### 1. Starship Capitalization Trigger & Commercialization Policy\n*   **The Trigger:** Starship will transition from the development stage to the commercial stage **once it is commercialized by delivering a payload to orbit**. The company expects to commence payload delivery to orbit in the **second half of 2026**.\n*   **The Policy:** Upon reaching this commercialization trigger, Starship costs will generally be **capitalized** as Property, Plant, and Equipment (PP&E). These capitalized costs will then be **depreciated into Cost of Revenue** for the specific segment associated with the payload delivered. \n\n---\n\n### 2. Development Stage vs. Commercial Stage Accounting\nThe accounting treatment for Starship shifts dramatically once the commercialization trigger is met. \n\n#### **Current State: Development Stage Accounting**\nBecause Starship is currently in the development stage, the company prioritizes rapid iteration and testing over near-term margin optimization. \n*   **Expensing as Incurred:** A majority of Starship costs are immediately expensed to **Research and Development (R&D)** as they are incurred. \n*   **What is Expensed:** R&D expenses include test flight hardware, tooling and equipment, employee compensation, allocated overhead, and depreciation for R&D equipment.\n*   **Test Flight Hardware:** Specifically, **Raptor engines are expensed** when they are used in test flights, rather than being capitalized as assets. (The company notes that test flights are for data collection, so even the loss of a vehicle is considered a learning milestone, not a traditional asset impairment).\n\n#### **Future State: Commercial Stage Accounting (Post-Trigger)**\nOnce Starship begins delivering commercial payloads to orbit, it will mirror the accounting treatment of the company\'s mature, commercialized vehicles (like Falcon 9, Falcon Heavy, and Dragon).\n*   **Capitalization:** Costs to build and refurbish the reusable Starship boosters, ships, and Raptor engines will be capitalized on the balance sheet as **Property, Plant, and Equipment (PP&E)**.\n*   **Depreciation Method:** Unlike standard PP&E which uses straight-line depreciation over an estimated useful life, **flight vehicles are depreciated based on the expected number of average flights** for each vehicle. This depreciation is recorded directly into **Cost of Revenue**.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Classification, Valuation, and Depreciation Methods\nThe Significant Accounting Policies dictate strict rules on how aerospace hardware is classified based on its reusability:\n\n#### **A. Reusable Components (Classified as PP&E)**\n*   **Assets Included:** Falcon 9/Heavy boosters (first stages), fairings, Merlin engines, Dragon capsules, and eventually Starship boosters/ships/Raptor engines.\n*   **Classification:** Classified as **Property, Plant, and Equipment, net**.\n*   **Valuation & Depreciation:** Stated at cost, less accumulated depreciation. Depreciation is computed based on the **expected number of average flights** per vehicle and charged to Cost of Revenue. Significant refurbishments or enhancements that increase functionality or expected life are capitalized and depreciated ratably over the identified useful life.\n\n#### **B. Non-Reusable Components (Classified as Inventory)**\n*   **Assets Included:** Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy **second stages** (which burn up upon reentry and are not reusable), as well as raw materials, work-in-progress, and finished goods awaiting launch.\n*   **Classification:** Recorded as **Inventory** until the moment of launch.\n*   **Valuation:** Computed using standard cost or weighted average (approximating FIFO) and stated at the **lower of cost or net realizable value**. The company records write-downs in Cost of Revenue for estimated obsolescence or unmarketable inventories based on future demand and design changes.\n*   **Revenue Recognition:** Second stages are transferred from Inventory and recorded directly to **Cost of Revenue** at the point in time they are launched (for Launch Services) or assigned (for Launch and Development contracts).\n\n#### **C. Internal / Inter-Segment Launches (e.g., Starlink)**\n*   When the Space segment launches the company\'s own Starlink satellites, **no inter-segment revenue is recognized**. \n*   Instead, the launch costs (including the allocation of flight vehicle depreciation and second-stage inventory) are **capitalized into the "Satellites" asset class** within PP&E, and subsequently depreciated over the satellites\' useful lives in the Connectivity segment.\n\n### Summary\nIn short, SpaceX treats **Starship currently as an R&D expense engine**, writing off test hardware and engines to accelerate innovation. However, the moment Starship achieves **orbital payload delivery (expected H2 2026)**, the accounting switch flips: hardware will be capitalized as PP&E, and costs will be matched against revenue via a **per-flight depreciation model**, mirroring the highly profitable, reusable economics of the Falcon 9.',
