n  - **Data center infrastructure:** 20–25 years\n- **Construction-in-progress (CIP):** AI infrastructure not yet placed in service is tracked as CIP on the balance sheet.\n- **Interest capitalization:** The filing explicitly states that interest is capitalized for "significant long-term construction projects," and specifically names **AI infrastructure data centers** as qualifying assets ($169 million capitalized in 2025).\n- **Relevance:** Orbital AI compute satellites are functionally "orbital data centers" — the AI infrastructure capitalization precedent supports treating the compute payload as a capital asset.\n\n#### 3. Starship Development-to-Commercialization Transition (Closest Stage-Gate Precedent)\n- **Development stage:** While Starship is in development, **a majority of costs are expensed to R&D as incurred** (including test flight hardware and Raptor engines used in test flights).\n- **Commercialization trigger:** Once Starship delivers a payload to orbit (expected H2 2026), costs will shift to being **capitalized as PP&E** and depreciated into Cost of Revenue on a per-flight basis.\n- **Relevance:** The filing explicitly categorizes orbital AI compute as being in the **"early stages of conception, design and development,"** mirroring Starship\'s current development-stage status. This strongly implies that current and near-term orbital AI compute costs are being expensed as R&D.\n\n---\n\n### Implied Treatment (Filing-Supported Inference)\n\nBased on the convergence of these precedents, the implied accounting treatment is **bifurcated by program stage**:\n\n| Phase | Likely Treatment | Supporting Precedent |\n|-------|-----------------|---------------------|\n| **Current: Conception, design, and development** | **Expensed as R&D** | Filing states orbital AI compute is in "early stages of conception, design and development" requiring "substantial ongoing investments in research and development." Starship development-stage precedent applies. |\n| **Future: Production and deployment of physical satellites** | **Capitalized as PP&E** (within "Satellites" and/or "Construction-in-progress") | Filing explicitly states the company expects to "allocate a significant amount [of launch capacity] to our AI segment in the future" and that internal launch costs are capitalized into PP&E. Existing satellite and AI infrastructure capitalization policies apply. |\n| **In-service: Operational orbital compute** | **Depreciated over estimated useful life** into Cost of Revenue (AI segment) | Analogous to Starlink satellite depreciation (straight-line, 3–5 years) and server depreciation (5–6 years). The filing notes that orbital hardware has a shorter physical lifespan than the IT systems it hosts, requiring constant replacement — suggesting a relatively short useful life. |\n\n---\n\n### Key Filing Quote on AI Segment Launch Allocation\n\nThe filing explicitly states:\n> The company currently allocates a significant amount of its launch capacity to its Connectivity segment and **"expects to allocate a significant amount to its AI segment in the future."**\n\nAnd on inter-segment accounting:\n> Launch costs for internal missions are **capitalized** within *Property, plant, and equipment, net* — no inter-segment revenue is recognized.\n\nThis is the strongest direct statement in the filing about how future AI-segment orbital assets would be treated: **capitalized, not expensed**, once they reach the deployment phase.\n\n---\n\n### Material Disclosure Gap\n\nThe filing does **not** specify:\n- A distinct useful life estimate for orbital AI compute satellites (vs. 3–5 years for Starlink or 5–6 years for servers)\n- Whether the compute payload and satellite bus would be depreciated as a single unit or bifurcated into separate asset categories with different useful lives\n- A specific commercialization trigger for orbital AI compute (analogous to Starship\'s "payload delivery to orbit" trigger)\n- Whether orbital AI compute satellites would be classified within the existing "Satellites" PP&E category, "Servers and networking equipment," or a new category\n\nThis absence of explicit guidance is itself analytically material, as the orbital AI compute initiative represents a potential capital expenditure program of unprecedented scale (the filing references a long-term vision of up to 100 gigawatts of space-based compute, requiring thousands of Starship launches per year).\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)"\n    }\n  ]\n}',
